Someone came to fix the floor in my kitchen, so I'll just pretend to still have a job and remote work while reviewing Too Hot to Handle.
If I can only manage to open this blasted file. (For crying out loud, OneDrive.)
For crying out loud, I'm on it.
And that's when it starts to drill really hard. Great!
His passive-aggressive way of running my air purifier at full blast makes me uneasy, but it smells like sawdust, so it's justified even if it's an anti-mask. And besides, I really do need to protect myself, don't I??
I'm too tired to go back to bed, but I won't be able to until he's gone.
The positive point is that I've finally finished re-reading chapter 4.
Chapter 5 is long, but lots of suspense. Good work.
I'm in the process of doing find-and-replace on … ➡️ the ellipsis character, and there are 54 of them in this chapter.
But, I'm sticking to it. The most natural speeches are mostly choppy, especially when people let themselves go with their emotions.
The repair worker is vacuuming, with any luck, he'll be done soon.
He's gone out (from what I can hear) to cut something. So, I took a peek to see how far along he is. It's far from being finished :(
More than 7 pages left on Chapter 5. That remains my favorite chapter, and it's quite well done. A few layout tweaks and minor changes to switch to the active voice and improve concision. That said, I could really use a break and a cup of tea, but the guy is still messing around in my kitchen.
He's just started vacuuming again. I hope that's a good sign.
The repair worker is gone.
He told me he drew up a quote for the entire floor, but the owners were stingy and only paid for the small damaged area near the door. That's a lot better.
The house is airing out, and my air purifier is running in the kitchen while I'm enjoying a cup of tea in the garden!
